### [to_frame()]{.doc-object-name .doc-function .doc-label .doc-label-method}

::: {.doc-subject}

Return the fitted survival curve(s) as a DataFrame.
:::

::: {.doc-usage-source}
Usage

[Source](https://github.com/rich-iannone/greenwood/blob/main/greenwood/_nonparametric.py#L810-L859){target="_blank" rel="noopener"}
:::

::: {.doc-signature .doc-Kind.FUNCTION}
```python
to_frame(*, format=None)
```
:::

::: {.doc-text}

Exports the Kaplan-Meier step function with one row per time point, including
risk-set counts, the survival estimate, its standard error, confidence limits, and
optional strata labels.
:::

#### Parameters {.doc-parameters}

::: {.doc-definition-items}
<code>[format]{.doc-parameter-name}[:]{.doc-parameter-annotation-sep} [str | None]{.doc-parameter-annotation} [=]{.doc-parameter-default-sep .op} [None]{.doc-parameter-default}</code>

:   Output format: `None` (default), `"pandas"`, `"polars"`, or `"pyarrow"`. When
    `None`, a backend is auto-detected (Polars, then Pandas, then PyArrow).
:::

#### Returns {.doc-returns}

::: {.doc-definition-items}
<code> [pandas.DataFrame, polars.DataFrame, or pyarrow.Table]{.doc-parameter-annotation}</code>

:   A tidy table with columns `time`, `n_risk`, `n_event`, `n_censor`, `estimate`,
    `std_error`, `conf_low`, `conf_high`, and optionally `strata`.
:::

#### Raises {.doc-raises}

::: {.doc-definition-items}
<code> [ImportError]{.doc-parameter-annotation}</code>

:   If the requested (or, when auto-detecting, any) DataFrame library is not
    installed.
:::

#### Examples {.doc-examples}

Fit a Kaplan-Meier estimator on the bundled `lung` dataset, then export the fitted
curve as a Polars frame:

::: {#58afdf36 .cell execution_count=11}
``` {.python .cell-code}
import greenwood as gw

# Load data and fit the Kaplan-Meier estimator
lung = gw.load_dataset("lung", backend="polars")
y = gw.Surv.right(lung["time"], event=(lung["status"] == 2))
km = gw.KaplanMeier().fit(y)

# Export the survival curve as a Polars DataFrame
km.to_frame(format="polars")
```

